Note:
JSX/TSX Lexer
Tokenizes JSX and TypeScript JSX syntax for the Translation translation system.

Features:
- JavaScript/TypeScript tokens (keywords, identifiers, operators, literals)
- JSX element tokens (tags, attributes, children)
- JSX expression tokens (embedded JavaScript within {})
- TypeScript type annotations
- Template literals
- Regular expressions
- Comments (single-line, multi-line, JSDoc)
- Proper closing tag detection (</TagName>)
:End Note

Import "compiler/frontend/primitives/memory/layout.runa" as Layout

Note:
Token Types
:End Note
Constant TOKEN_EOF as Integer is 0
Constant TOKEN_IDENTIFIER as Integer is 1
Constant TOKEN_KEYWORD as Integer is 2
Constant TOKEN_STRING as Integer is 3
Constant TOKEN_NUMBER as Integer is 4
Constant TOKEN_TEMPLATE_LITERAL as Integer is 5
Constant TOKEN_REGEX as Integer is 6
Constant TOKEN_JSX_TAG_OPEN as Integer is 10
Constant TOKEN_JSX_TAG_CLOSE as Integer is 11
Constant TOKEN_JSX_TAG_SELF_CLOSE as Integer is 12
Constant TOKEN_JSX_CLOSING_TAG_START as Integer is 13
Constant TOKEN_JSX_ATTRIBUTE as Integer is 14
Constant TOKEN_JSX_TEXT as Integer is 15
Constant TOKEN_JSX_EXPRESSION_START as Integer is 16
Constant TOKEN_JSX_EXPRESSION_END as Integer is 17
Constant TOKEN_JSX_FRAGMENT_OPEN as Integer is 18
Constant TOKEN_JSX_FRAGMENT_CLOSE as Integer is 19
Constant TOKEN_LPAREN as Integer is 20
Constant TOKEN_RPAREN as Integer is 21
Constant TOKEN_LBRACE as Integer is 22
Constant TOKEN_RBRACE as Integer is 23
Constant TOKEN_LBRACKET as Integer is 24
Constant TOKEN_RBRACKET as Integer is 25
Constant TOKEN_DOT as Integer is 26
Constant TOKEN_COMMA as Integer is 27
Constant TOKEN_SEMICOLON as Integer is 28
Constant TOKEN_COLON as Integer is 29
Constant TOKEN_QUESTION as Integer is 30
Constant TOKEN_ARROW as Integer is 31
Constant TOKEN_SPREAD as Integer is 32
Constant TOKEN_ASSIGN as Integer is 40
Constant TOKEN_PLUS as Integer is 41
Constant TOKEN_MINUS as Integer is 42
Constant TOKEN_STAR as Integer is 43
Constant TOKEN_SLASH as Integer is 44
Constant TOKEN_PERCENT as Integer is 45
Constant TOKEN_LT as Integer is 46
Constant TOKEN_GT as Integer is 47
Constant TOKEN_LE as Integer is 48
Constant TOKEN_GE as Integer is 49
Constant TOKEN_EQ as Integer is 50
Constant TOKEN_NE as Integer is 51
Constant TOKEN_AND as Integer is 52
Constant TOKEN_OR as Integer is 53
Constant TOKEN_NOT as Integer is 54
Constant TOKEN_BITWISE_AND as Integer is 55
Constant TOKEN_BITWISE_OR as Integer is 56
Constant TOKEN_BITWISE_XOR as Integer is 57
Constant TOKEN_BITWISE_NOT as Integer is 58
Constant TOKEN_COMMENT as Integer is 60
Constant TOKEN_ERROR as Integer is 99

Note:
Lexer structure
Fields:
- source (0): Source code string pointer
- position (8): Current position in source
- length (16): Total source length
- line (24): Current line number
- column (32): Current column number
- jsx_depth (40): Depth of JSX element nesting (0 = not in JSX)
- brace_depth (48): Depth of brace nesting within JSX expressions
- in_tag (56): 1 while scanning an opening/closing tag header (between
  '<tag' and the terminating '>' / '/>'), 0 in element body or JS context.
  This is what distinguishes "attribute identifiers / '=' / string / '{'"
  tokenization inside a tag header from "verbatim text run" tokenization in
  an element body. Without it the tag name and attributes would be swallowed
  as a single JSX_TEXT run.
:End Note

Note:
Token structure
Fields:
- type (0): Token type constant
- text (8): Token text pointer
- text_length (16): Length of token text
- line (24): Line number where token appears
- column (32): Column number where token starts
- value (40): Optional numeric or additional value
:End Note

@Reasoning:
The lexer is a 64-byte struct (eight 8-byte slots) holding source pointer, cursor position, total length, line/column tracking, and three state slots: JSX element nesting depth, brace nesting depth within JSX expressions, and the in-tag-header flag. Bundling these makes peek/advance O(1) without dict lookups.
@End Reasoning
@Implementation:
Field layout: 0=source, 8=position, 16=length, 24=line (1-based), 32=column (1-based), 40=jsx_depth, 48=brace_depth, 56=in_tag. Line/column start at 1 because users expect 1-based diagnostics. Source is borrowed (caller owns the buffer for the lexer's lifetime).
@End Implementation
Process called "create_lexer" takes source as Integer, length as Integer returns Integer:
    Let lexer be proc allocate from Layout with 64

    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with lexer, 0, source
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with lexer, 8, 0
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with lexer, 16, length
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with lexer, 24, 1
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with lexer, 32, 1
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with lexer, 40, 0
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with lexer, 48, 0
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with lexer, 56, 0

    Return lexer
End Process

@Reasoning:
A token is a 48-byte record bundling type, text pointer (zero-copy view into source), text length, line/column, and one extensible value slot for numeric token values or interned identifier IDs. Six 8-byte slots accommodate the parser's typical access patterns without re-reading from source.
@End Reasoning
@Implementation:
text is a pointer back into the original source buffer, so token text validity depends on the source outliving the token; the caller (parser) is responsible for that lifetime contract. The value slot is intentionally a single Integer so the same record shape serves numeric literals (encoded value), regex flags, template-literal indices, and identifier IDs.
@End Implementation
Process called "create_token" takes type as Integer, text as Integer, text_length as Integer, line as Integer, column as Integer, value as Integer returns Integer:
    Let token be proc allocate from Layout with 48

    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with token, 0, type
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with token, 8, text
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with token, 16, text_length
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with token, 24, line
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with token, 32, column
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with token, 40, value

    Return token
End Process

@Reasoning:
peek_char returns 0 at end-of-input rather than -1 or a sentinel so callers can branch on `is equal to 0` without special-casing. 0 is safe because legitimate JSX/JS source never contains a NUL byte mid-file (NUL would terminate the source string in any C-compatible representation).
@End Reasoning
Process called "peek_char" takes lexer as Integer returns Integer:
    Let source be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with lexer, 0
    Let position be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with lexer, 8
    Let length be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with lexer, 16

    If position is greater than or equal to length:
        Return 0
    End If

    Let char be proc memory_get_byte from Layout with source, position
    Return char
End Process

@Reasoning:
JSX disambiguation requires multi-character lookahead: "<" alone vs "</" vs "<!--" all need 1-2 chars beyond the cursor before the lexer commits to a path. An explicit offset parameter (not just "peek next") lets callers look arbitrarily far without per-arity wrappers.
@End Reasoning
Process called "peek_ahead" takes lexer as Integer, offset as Integer returns Integer:
    Let source be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with lexer, 0
    Let position be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with lexer, 8
    Let length be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with lexer, 16
    Let look_pos be position plus offset

    If look_pos is greater than or equal to length:
        Return 0
    End If

    Let char be proc memory_get_byte from Layout with source, look_pos
    Return char
End Process

@Reasoning:
advance_char both moves the cursor and maintains line/column state in one pass; doing both here means every other production sees correct location info "for free". Newline (ASCII 10) resets column to 1 and bumps line; carriage-return (13) is not handled specially because the spec defines line counts by LF, and CRLF input has the LF counted on the second byte.
@End Reasoning
Process called "advance_char" takes lexer as Integer returns Integer:
    Let position be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with lexer, 8
    Let length be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with lexer, 16

    If position is greater than or equal to length:
        Return 0
    End If

    Let source be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with lexer, 0
    Let char be proc memory_get_byte from Layout with source, position

    Set position to position plus 1
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with lexer, 8, position

    Let column be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with lexer, 32

    If char is equal to 10:
        Let line be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with lexer, 24
        Set line to line plus 1
        proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with lexer, 24, line
        proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with lexer, 32, 1
        Return char
    End If

    Set column to column plus 1
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with lexer, 32, column

    Return char
End Process

@Reasoning:
The JS/JSX whitespace set is space (32), tab (9), LF (10), and CR (13); the four explicit branches are faster than a table lookup for this small fixed set and mirror the ECMA-262 whitespace definition used in everyday JS source.
@End Reasoning
Process called "is_whitespace" takes char as Integer returns Integer:
    If char is equal to 32:
        Return 1
    End If
    If char is equal to 9:
        Return 1
    End If
    If char is equal to 10:
        Return 1
    End If
    If char is equal to 13:
        Return 1
    End If
    Return 0
End Process

@Reasoning:
JS identifiers may begin with [A-Za-z_$]; underscore (95) and dollar (36) are explicit because they're outside the contiguous letter ranges. Unicode identifier characters are not handled here — they would require a separate is_unicode_id_start predicate (deferred to the parser's identifier scanner if a non-ASCII start is detected).
@End Reasoning
Process called "is_alpha" takes char as Integer returns Integer:
    If char is greater than or equal to 65:
        If char is less than or equal to 90:
            Return 1
        End If
    End If
    If char is greater than or equal to 97:
        If char is less than or equal to 122:
            Return 1
        End If
    End If
    If char is equal to 95:
        Return 1
    End If
    If char is equal to 36:
        Return 1
    End If
    Return 0
End Process

@Reasoning:
ASCII digits 0-9 occupy code points 48-57; the range check is the canonical fast-path. JS BigInt literals (e.g., 42n) are handled at scan_number rather than here.
@End Reasoning
Process called "is_digit" takes char as Integer returns Integer:
    If char is greater than or equal to 48:
        If char is less than or equal to 57:
            Return 1
        End If
    End If
    Return 0
End Process

@Reasoning:
Hex digits cover 0-9, A-F, and a-f; we delegate the digit check to is_digit and add the two letter ranges. JS hex escapes (\\x.., \\u....) and hex numeric literals (0x...) share this predicate.
@End Reasoning
Process called "is_hex_digit" takes char as Integer returns Integer:
    Let is_digit_result be proc is_digit with char
    If is_digit_result is equal to 1:
        Return 1
    End If
    If char is greater than or equal to 65:
        If char is less than or equal to 70:
            Return 1
        End If
    End If
    If char is greater than or equal to 97:
        If char is less than or equal to 102:
            Return 1
        End If
    End If
    Return 0
End Process

@Reasoning:
JS identifier continuation characters are letters + digits + _ + $; we reuse is_alpha (which already handles _ and $) and add is_digit. The order matters for hit-rate: most identifier-body characters are letters, so checking is_alpha first short-circuits faster on the common case.
@End Reasoning
Process called "is_identifier_char" takes char as Integer returns Integer:
    Let is_alpha_result be proc is_alpha with char
    If is_alpha_result is equal to 1:
        Return 1
    End If
    Let is_digit_result be proc is_digit with char
    If is_digit_result is equal to 1:
        Return 1
    End If
    Return 0
End Process

@Reasoning:
Whitespace skipping is a hot path so we loop in tight peek/advance pairs; the `Break` exit when a non-whitespace char appears (or end-of-source returns 0) keeps the inner loop predictable for branch prediction. Comments are NOT skipped here because they're tokenized as TOKEN_COMMENT for tooling that wants to preserve them (formatters, doc generators).
@End Reasoning
Process called "skip_whitespace" takes lexer as Integer returns Integer:
    While 1 is equal to 1:
        Let char be proc peek_char with lexer
        Let is_ws be proc is_whitespace with char

        If is_ws is equal to 0:
            Break
        End If

        proc advance_char with lexer
    End While

    Return 1
End Process

@Reasoning:
JS has two comment forms — // (single-line, ends at LF) and /* */ (multi-line) — both starting with /. We discriminate via the second character (47=/ or 42=*) and emit a single TOKEN_COMMENT spanning the entire comment text including the delimiters; this preserves the original source for formatters and IDEs. End-of-file inside a /* */ terminates the comment without error (lenient to truncated input).
@End Reasoning
Process called "scan_comment" takes lexer as Integer returns Integer:
    Let source be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with lexer, 0
    Let start_position be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with lexer, 8
    Let line be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with lexer, 24
    Let column be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with lexer, 32

    Let first_char be proc peek_char with lexer
    Let second_char be proc peek_ahead with lexer, 1

    Note:
    Single-line comment
    :End Note
    If first_char is equal to 47:
        If second_char is equal to 47:
            proc advance_char with lexer
            proc advance_char with lexer

            While 1 is equal to 1:
                Let char be proc peek_char with lexer

                If char is equal to 0:
                    Break
                End If

                If char is equal to 10:
                    Break
                End If

                proc advance_char with lexer
            End While

            Let end_position be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with lexer, 8
            Let length be end_position minus start_position
            Let text_ptr be source plus start_position

            Return proc create_token with TOKEN_COMMENT, text_ptr, length, line, column, 0
        End If
    End If

    Note:
    Multi-line comment
    :End Note
    If first_char is equal to 47:
        If second_char is equal to 42:
            proc advance_char with lexer
            proc advance_char with lexer

            While 1 is equal to 1:
                Set char to proc peek_char with lexer

                If char is equal to 0:
                    Break
                End If

                If char is equal to 42:
                    Let next_char be proc peek_ahead with lexer, 1
                    If next_char is equal to 47:
                        proc advance_char with lexer
                        proc advance_char with lexer
                        Break
                    End If
                End If

                proc advance_char with lexer
            End While

            Set end_position to proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with lexer, 8
            Set length to end_position minus start_position
            Set text_ptr to source plus start_position

            Return proc create_token with TOKEN_COMMENT, text_ptr, length, line, column, 0
        End If
    End If

    Return 0
End Process

@Reasoning:
Identifier scanning is the standard "consume while is_identifier_char" loop. After scanning, check_keyword reclassifies the text into TOKEN_KEYWORD if it matches a reserved word — this maximum-munch approach is correct because JS keywords and identifiers share the same lexical shape and only differ by exact text.
@End Reasoning
Process called "scan_identifier" takes lexer as Integer returns Integer:
    Let source be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with lexer, 0
    Let start_position be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with lexer, 8
    Let line be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with lexer, 24
    Let column be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with lexer, 32

    While 1 is equal to 1:
        Let char be proc peek_char with lexer
        Let is_id_char be proc is_identifier_char with char

        If is_id_char is equal to 0:
            Break
        End If

        proc advance_char with lexer
    End While

    Let end_position be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with lexer, 8
    Let length be end_position minus start_position
    Let text_ptr be source plus start_position

    Let token_type be proc check_keyword with text_ptr, length

    Return proc create_token with token_type, text_ptr, length, line, column, 0
End Process

@Reasoning:
Keyword recognition uses length-bucketed character comparison (length first, then per-position byte checks) rather than a string hash table because the JS reserved-word set is small and the per-bucket comparison is a few branches at most. The bucketing prevents wasted work — a 5-char input never touches the 6-char keyword cases.
@End Reasoning
@Performance_Hints:
This is a hot path (called once per identifier); the length-then-byte structure outperforms hash-based lookup for small fixed sets because it avoids allocator/hash overhead and stays in registers.
@End Performance_Hints
Process called "check_keyword" takes text as Integer, length as Integer returns Integer:
    Note:
    Check for JavaScript/TypeScript keywords
    :End Note

    If length is equal to 2:
        Let c0 be proc memory_get_byte from Layout with text, 0
        Let c1 be proc memory_get_byte from Layout with text, 1

        If c0 is equal to 105:
            If c1 is equal to 102:
                Return TOKEN_KEYWORD
            End If
        End If

        If c0 is equal to 100:
            If c1 is equal to 111:
                Return TOKEN_KEYWORD
            End If
        End If

        If c0 is equal to 105:
            If c1 is equal to 110:
                Return TOKEN_KEYWORD
            End If
        End If
    End If

    If length is equal to 3:
        Set c0 to proc memory_get_byte from Layout with text, 0
        Set c1 to proc memory_get_byte from Layout with text, 1
        Let c2 be proc memory_get_byte from Layout with text, 2

        If c0 is equal to 118:
            If c1 is equal to 97:
                If c2 is equal to 114:
                    Return TOKEN_KEYWORD
                End If
            End If
        End If

        If c0 is equal to 108:
            If c1 is equal to 101:
                If c2 is equal to 116:
                    Return TOKEN_KEYWORD
                End If
            End If
        End If

        If c0 is equal to 102:
            If c1 is equal to 111:
                If c2 is equal to 114:
                    Return TOKEN_KEYWORD
                End If
            End If
        End If

        If c0 is equal to 110:
            If c1 is equal to 101:
                If c2 is equal to 119:
                    Return TOKEN_KEYWORD
                End If
            End If
        End If

        If c0 is equal to 116:
            If c1 is equal to 114:
                If c2 is equal to 121:
                    Return TOKEN_KEYWORD
                End If
            End If
        End If
    End If

    If length is equal to 4:
        Set c0 to proc memory_get_byte from Layout with text, 0
        Set c1 to proc memory_get_byte from Layout with text, 1
        Set c2 to proc memory_get_byte from Layout with text, 2
        Let c3 be proc memory_get_byte from Layout with text, 3

        If c0 is equal to 116:
            If c1 is equal to 104:
                If c2 is equal to 105:
                    If c3 is equal to 115:
                        Return TOKEN_KEYWORD
                    End If
                End If
            End If
        End If

        If c0 is equal to 101:
            If c1 is equal to 108:
                If c2 is equal to 115:
                    If c3 is equal to 101:
                        Return TOKEN_KEYWORD
                    End If
                End If
            End If
        End If

        If c0 is equal to 99:
            If c1 is equal to 97:
                If c2 is equal to 115:
                    If c3 is equal to 101:
                        Return TOKEN_KEYWORD
                    End If
                End If
            End If
        End If

        If c0 is equal to 101:
            If c1 is equal to 110:
                If c2 is equal to 117:
                    If c3 is equal to 109:
                        Return TOKEN_KEYWORD
                    End If
                End If
            End If
        End If

        If c0 is equal to 116:
            If c1 is equal to 121:
                If c2 is equal to 112:
                    If c3 is equal to 101:
                        Return TOKEN_KEYWORD
                    End If
                End If
            End If
        End If

        If c0 is equal to 110:
            If c1 is equal to 117:
                If c2 is equal to 108:
                    If c3 is equal to 108:
                        Return TOKEN_KEYWORD
                    End If
                End If
            End If
        End If

        If c0 is equal to 116:
            If c1 is equal to 114:
                If c2 is equal to 117:
                    If c3 is equal to 101:
                        Return TOKEN_KEYWORD
                    End If
                End If
            End If
        End If

        If c0 is equal to 118:
            If c1 is equal to 111:
                If c2 is equal to 105:
                    If c3 is equal to 100:
                        Return TOKEN_KEYWORD
                    End If
                End If
            End If
        End If
    End If

    If length is equal to 5:
        Set c0 to proc memory_get_byte from Layout with text, 0
        Set c1 to proc memory_get_byte from Layout with text, 1
        Set c2 to proc memory_get_byte from Layout with text, 2
        Set c3 to proc memory_get_byte from Layout with text, 3
        Let c4 be proc memory_get_byte from Layout with text, 4

        If c0 is equal to 99:
            If c1 is equal to 111:
                If c2 is equal to 110:
                    If c3 is equal to 115:
                        If c4 is equal to 116:
                            Return TOKEN_KEYWORD
                        End If
                    End If
                End If
            End If
        End If

        If c0 is equal to 98:
            If c1 is equal to 114:
                If c2 is equal to 101:
                    If c3 is equal to 97:
                        If c4 is equal to 107:
                            Return TOKEN_KEYWORD
                        End If
                    End If
                End If
            End If
        End If

        If c0 is equal to 99:
            If c1 is equal to 97:
                If c2 is equal to 116:
                    If c3 is equal to 99:
                        If c4 is equal to 104:
                            Return TOKEN_KEYWORD
                        End If
                    End If
                End If
            End If
        End If

        If c0 is equal to 116:
            If c1 is equal to 104:
                If c2 is equal to 114:
                    If c3 is equal to 111:
                        If c4 is equal to 119:
                            Return TOKEN_KEYWORD
                        End If
                    End If
                End If
            End If
        End If

        If c0 is equal to 119:
            If c1 is equal to 104:
                If c2 is equal to 105:
                    If c3 is equal to 108:
                        If c4 is equal to 101:
                            Return TOKEN_KEYWORD
                        End If
                    End If
                End If
            End If
        End If

        If c0 is equal to 97:
            If c1 is equal to 115:
                If c2 is equal to 121:
                    If c3 is equal to 110:
                        If c4 is equal to 99:
                            Return TOKEN_KEYWORD
                        End If
                    End If
                End If
            End If
        End If

        If c0 is equal to 97:
            If c1 is equal to 119:
                If c2 is equal to 97:
                    If c3 is equal to 105:
                        If c4 is equal to 116:
                            Return TOKEN_KEYWORD
                        End If
                    End If
                End If
            End If
        End If

        If c0 is equal to 99:
            If c1 is equal to 108:
                If c2 is equal to 97:
                    If c3 is equal to 115:
                        If c4 is equal to 115:
                            Return TOKEN_KEYWORD
                        End If
                    End If
                End If
            End If
        End If

        If c0 is equal to 102:
            If c1 is equal to 97:
                If c2 is equal to 108:
                    If c3 is equal to 115:
                        If c4 is equal to 101:
                            Return TOKEN_KEYWORD
                        End If
                    End If
                End If
            End If
        End If

        If c0 is equal to 115:
            If c1 is equal to 117:
                If c2 is equal to 112:
                    If c3 is equal to 101:
                        If c4 is equal to 114:
                            Return TOKEN_KEYWORD
                        End If
                    End If
                End If
            End If
        End If

        If c0 is equal to 121:
            If c1 is equal to 105:
                If c2 is equal to 101:
                    If c3 is equal to 108:
                        If c4 is equal to 100:
                            Return TOKEN_KEYWORD
                        End If
                    End If
                End If
            End If
        End If
    End If

    If length is equal to 6:
        Set c0 to proc memory_get_byte from Layout with text, 0
        Set c1 to proc memory_get_byte from Layout with text, 1
        Set c2 to proc memory_get_byte from Layout with text, 2

        If c0 is equal to 114:
            If c1 is equal to 101:
                If c2 is equal to 116:
                    Return TOKEN_KEYWORD
                End If
            End If
        End If

        If c0 is equal to 105:
            If c1 is equal to 109:
                If c2 is equal to 112:
                    Return TOKEN_KEYWORD
                End If
            End If
        End If

        If c0 is equal to 101:
            If c1 is equal to 120:
                If c2 is equal to 112:
                    Return TOKEN_KEYWORD
                End If
            End If
        End If

        If c0 is equal to 100:
            If c1 is equal to 101:
                If c2 is equal to 108:
                    Return TOKEN_KEYWORD
                End If
            End If
        End If

        If c0 is equal to 115:
            If c1 is equal to 119:
                If c2 is equal to 105:
                    Return TOKEN_KEYWORD
                End If
            End If
        End If

        If c0 is equal to 116:
            If c1 is equal to 121:
                If c2 is equal to 112:
                    Return TOKEN_KEYWORD
                End If
            End If
        End If

        If c0 is equal to 112:
            If c1 is equal to 117:
                If c2 is equal to 98:
                    Return TOKEN_KEYWORD
                End If
            End If
        End If

        If c0 is equal to 115:
            If c1 is equal to 116:
                If c2 is equal to 97:
                    Return TOKEN_KEYWORD
                End If
            End If
        End If
    End If

    If length is equal to 7:
        Set c0 to proc memory_get_byte from Layout with text, 0
        Set c1 to proc memory_get_byte from Layout with text, 1
        Set c2 to proc memory_get_byte from Layout with text, 2

        If c0 is equal to 100:
            If c1 is equal to 101:
                If c2 is equal to 102:
                    Return TOKEN_KEYWORD
                End If
            End If
        End If

        If c0 is equal to 101:
            If c1 is equal to 120:
                If c2 is equal to 116:
                    Return TOKEN_KEYWORD
                End If
            End If
