@Reasoning:
JS supports two string forms ('...' and "...") with identical escape rules; passing the quote character as a parameter lets one function handle both. Backslash escapes are consumed greedily (advance past the backslash AND the following char) so escape sequences containing the quote character don't terminate the string prematurely. EOF mid-string is tolerated (loop breaks on 0) rather than emitting a fatal error so partial source can still be tokenized for editor completion.
@End Reasoning
@Security_Scope:
The token text points back into the source buffer with no copy; the parser owns string-content interpretation including escape decoding. This keeps the lexer side-effect-free with respect to string content and avoids unbounded memory growth on adversarial input with many escapes.
@End Security_Scope
