End Process

@Reasoning:
Template literals (backtick strings) embed expressions via ${...}; we track brace depth so a closing backtick INSIDE an embedded expression doesn't prematurely terminate the literal. The brace depth also handles nested objects/arrays inside the embedded expression. Backslash escapes consume two characters to avoid escape-sequence interactions with the depth counter.
@End Reasoning
@Implementation:
The whole template (including embedded expressions) is captured as a single TOKEN_TEMPLATE_LITERAL; the parser re-lexes the embedded expressions on demand. This keeps the lexer's state machine flat and avoids needing a sub-lexer for the expression portions.
@End Implementation
